data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both compiled and ran without issues:

```csharp
Span<nint>  signedSpan   = stackalloc nint[4];
Span<nuint> unsignedSpan = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

On this 64-bit system, `nint` is 8 bytes, so `nint.MaxValue` is `9223372036854775807` and `nuint.MaxValue` is `18446744073709551615` — the standard `long`/`ulong` max values. This feature has been available since C# 9 / .NET 5 when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types.
